Thread Lifecycle and Methods

Interview Questions
1) Explain the lifecycle (states) of a thread in Java?
-->The thread lifecycle represents the different stages a thread goes through from creation to termination.
    
    A thread in Java moves through several states during its execution.
    
    Lifecycle Flow
    NEW → RUNNABLE → RUNNING → WAITING/BLOCKED/TIMED_WAITING → TERMINATED
    Explanation
    1.NEW
        Thread object is created but not started.
    2.RUNNABLE
        Thread is ready to run and waiting for CPU.
    3.RUNNING
        Thread is currently executing.
    4.WAITING / BLOCKED / TIMED_WAITING
        Thread is temporarily inactive due to waiting, sleeping, joining, or lock access.
    5.TERMINATED (DEAD)
        Thread execution is completed.

2) What are the different states in a thread’s lifecycle?
-->Java provides the following thread states through:
    
    Thread.State
    States of a Thread
    State	Description
        NEW	-->Thread created but not started
        RUNNABLE-->	Ready for execution
        BLOCKED	-->Waiting to acquire lock
        WAITING	-->Waiting indefinitely
        TIMED_WAITING-->	Waiting for specified time
        TERMINATED-->	Thread execution completed



3) What is the difference between start() and run() method?
-->
| `start()`                           | `run()`                    |
| ----------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Creates a new thread                | Normal method call         |
| JVM internally calls `run()`        | Executes in current thread |
| Executes concurrently               | No multithreading          |
| Thread scheduler controls execution | Runs sequentially          |

class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Child Thread");
    }
}

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t = new MyThread();

        t.start(); // Creates new thread
    }
}



4) What happens if we call run() directly instead of start()?
-->If run() is called directly:
      
      No new thread is created
      It behaves like a normal method call
      Execution happens inside the main thread only
      Example
      class MyThread extends Thread {
          public void run() {
              System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName());
          }
      }
      
      class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              MyThread t = new MyThread();
      
              t.run(); // Direct method call
          }
      }
      Output
      main
      Important Point
      start()
      
      creates a new thread.
      
      run()
      
      does not create a new thread.


5) What does the join() method do?
-->The join() method is used to make one thread wait until another thread completes execution.
      
      Syntax
      t.join();
      Example
      class MyThread extends Thread {
          public void run() {
              for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {
                  System.out.println(i);
              }
          }
      }
      
      class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
              MyThread t = new MyThread();
      
              t.start();
      
              t.join();
      
              System.out.println("Main Thread Ends");
          }
      }
      Output
      1
      2
      3
      4
      5
      Main Thread Ends
      
      Main thread waits until child thread finishes.
      

6) What is the sleep() method?
-->The sleep() method temporarily pauses the execution of the current thread for a specified time.

    Syntax
    Thread.sleep(milliseconds);
    Example
    class Demo {
        public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    
            for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {
    
                System.out.println(i);
    
                Thread.sleep(1000);
            }
        }
    }
    Output
    
    Numbers print every 1 second.
    
    Important Points
    sleep() is a static method
    Causes TIMED_WAITING state
    Does not release locks



7) What does yield() do?
-->The yield() method pauses the currently executing thread temporarily and gives a chance to other threads of same priority to execute.
    
    Syntax
      Thread.yield();
      Important Points
      It is a static method
      It is only a suggestion to the thread scheduler
      Scheduler may ignore it
      Example
        Thread.yield();


8) What is interrupt(), and how does it work?
-->The interrupt() method is used to interrupt a thread that is in sleeping or waiting state.
    
    Syntax
    t.interrupt();
    Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void run() {
    
            try {
                Thread.sleep(5000);
            }
            catch(InterruptedException e) {
                System.out.println("Thread Interrupted");
            }
        }
    }
    
    class Demo {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            MyThread t = new MyThread();
    
            t.start();
    
            t.interrupt();
        }
    }
    Output
    Thread Interrupted



9) What is the isAlive() method used for?
-->The isAlive() method checks whether a thread is currently running or not.
      
      Syntax
      t.isAlive();
      Return Type
      true → thread is running
      false → thread is not running
      Example
      class MyThread extends Thread {
      
          public void run() {
              System.out.println("Running");
          }
      }
      
      class Demo {
      
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              MyThread t = new MyThread();
      
              System.out.println(t.isAlive());
      
              t.start();
      
              System.out.println(t.isAlive());
          }
      }



10) What is the difference among sleep(), join() and yield()?
-->
| Method    | Purpose                           | Affects Which Thread | Releases Lock           | Waiting Type   |
| --------- | --------------------------------- | -------------------- | ----------------------- | -------------- |
| `sleep()` | Pause current thread              | Current thread       | No                      | Timed waiting  |
| `join()`  | Wait for another thread to finish | Calling thread       | Yes (generally waiting) | Waiting        |
| `yield()` | Give chance to other threads      | Current thread       | No                      | Runnable state |



11) Can we restart a dead thread in Java?
-->No, we cannot restart a dead thread in Java.
    
    Once a thread completes execution:
    
    It enters TERMINATED state
    Calling start() again throws:
    IllegalThreadStateException
    Example
    class MyThread extends Thread {
    
        public void run() {
            System.out.println("Running");
        }
    }
    
    class Demo {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            MyThread t = new MyThread();
    
            t.start();
    
            t.start(); // Exception
        }
    }
    Output
    Exception in thread "main"
    java.lang.IllegalThreadStateException
